       <p>For example, selecting a Burrito Tortilla immediately adds 320 calories and 50g of carbohydrates to your total. If you apply a <code>double</code> multiplier to your protein selection, the script dynamically scales the associated macro arrays by a factor of 2.0.</p>

       <h3>Optimizing Your Macros</h3>
+      <p>Building an optimal meal requires understanding trade-offs. If your goal is maximizing protein while minimizing caloric intake, the most efficient approach is avoiding the tortilla and skipping the cheese, sour cream, and guacamole entirely. By focusing on double chicken or double steak combined with a salad base and lighter salsas (such as the tomatillo green-chili salsa or fresh tomato salsa), you can achieve over 60 grams of protein for under 500 calories. This ratio is exceptionally favorable for bodybuilders or anyone pursuing a recomposition phase.</p>
+
+      <p>On the other hand, endurance athletes or individuals looking to fuel a heavy training session may prioritize complex carbohydrates. In this scenario, adding both white and brown rice along with black beans provides a dense, sustained energy source. While the caloric load increases significantly, the macronutrient profile shifts to support glycogen replenishment. It is critical to recognize that not all calories are created equal; the metabolic response to a 1,000-calorie bowl rich in complex carbs and lean protein is vastly different from a 1,000-calorie meal composed primarily of saturated fats and simple sugars.</p>
+
+      <h3>The Impact of Fats and Hidden Calories</h3>
+      <p>One of the most common pitfalls when ordering at fast-casual dining establishments is underestimating the caloric density of dietary fats. While fats are an essential component of a balanced diet—crucial for hormone synthesis and nutrient absorption—they are significantly more calorie-dense than proteins or carbohydrates. A single gram of fat contains 9 calories, compared to just 4 calories per gram for protein and carbs.</p>
+
+      <p>At Chipotle, the primary sources of dietary fat are the guacamole, sour cream, cheese, and queso blanco. Adding just one serving of guacamole and sour cream increases your meal by 340 calories and 31 grams of fat. For someone on a strict caloric deficit, this single addition can easily negate an entire day's progress. Our <strong>chipotle nutrition calculator</strong> visually isolates these variables, allowing you to instantly see how substituting sour cream for an extra serving of fajita veggies alters the final macro profile without sacrificing flavor.</p>
+
+      <h3>Sodium and Micronutrient Considerations</h3>
+      <p>While this tool focuses exclusively on the primary macronutrients (calories, protein, carbs, and fats), it is also important to consider the micronutrient profile of your meal, particularly sodium. Restaurant food is notoriously high in sodium, which is used extensively for flavor enhancement and preservation. Ingredients like the barbacoa, fresh tomato salsa, and the tomatillo red-chili salsa can significantly increase the sodium content of your bowl.</p>
+
+      <p>High sodium intake can lead to temporary water retention and bloating, which can sometimes be mistakenly perceived as fat gain on the scale. If you are tracking your weight daily, be mindful that a highly seasoned restaurant meal may cause acute fluctuations in body weight. To mitigate this, consider drinking additional water and ensuring your potassium intake is adequate to balance the intracellular fluid levels.</p>
+
+      <h3>Vegetarian and Vegan Dietary Tracking</h3>
+      <p>For individuals adhering to plant-based diets, navigating restaurant menus requires a different strategic approach. Without animal proteins, securing an adequate amino acid profile often relies on complementary plant sources. At Chipotle, combining black or pinto beans with rice forms a complete protein, providing all essential amino acids required by the body.</p>
+
+      <p>Alternatively, the sofritas—a seasoned, shredded tofu option—offers 8 grams of protein per serving alongside 10 grams of fat. While lower in protein density compared to chicken or steak, it serves as an excellent vegan alternative. Our calculator allows plant-based eaters to experiment with different combinations, perhaps opting for double beans and sofritas to reach their specific protein thresholds while monitoring the associated carbohydrate load.</p>
+
+      <h3>Conclusion</h3>
+      <p>Ultimately, dietary success is driven by consistency, precision, and adherence to a specific energy balance protocol. Whether you rely on intuitive eating or strict macro tracking, having access to transparent, real-time data eliminates the guesswork associated with dining out. By utilizing this calculator before you order, you can confidently build a meal that aligns perfectly with your physical goals, ensuring that your nutrition supports your training rather than hindering it.</p>
+
       <p>If you are tracking macros closely, use this tool to experiment with different combinations. A common optimization for high protein and lower calories is selecting a salad bowl base, double chicken, skipping the rice and beans, and relying on fajita veggies and fresh tomato salsa for flavor and volume. This yields roughly 395 calories and an impressive 65g of protein.</p>

       <p>Conversely, if you need a high-calorie meal to meet bulking requirements, wrapping your meal in a tortilla and adding rice, beans, sour cream, and guacamole will easily push the total well past 1,200 calories.</p>
